{"type":"message","id":"de359129","parentId":"2e114f10","timestamp":"2026-06-03T22:45:15.585Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"chatcmpl-tool-987d0c8ce052518e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Agentic Sandbox Project (AIOS) - Ground Truth Reference Document\n\n## 1. Project Vision and Motivation\n* **Core Concept**: Design and build an industry-informed agentic innovation infrastructure, referred to as an Agentic Operating System (AIOS) or \"Sandbox\".\n* **Vision**: Create a controlled, isolated environment where deployed AI agents can execute tasks (perceive, reason, act) and collaborate with other agents without producing unintended consequences or affecting real-world enterprise systems.\n* **Motivation**: As organizations shift towards enterprise systems composed of multiple autonomous agents, the Sandbox answers a critical architectural question: *How do we architect these systems well?* It allows organizations to safely address \"what-if\" scenarios. Furthermore, it facilitates the translation of university-based AI inventions into practical industry solutions.\n* **Target Partners**: University researchers, industry organizations, non-profit organizations, and government entities.\n\n## 2. Core Features and Capabilities\nThe AIOS Sandbox will be designed to offer the following high-level capabilities:\n* **Multi-Agent Simulation**: Simulate complex AI solutions composed of a network of collaborating AI agents.\n* **Workflow Orchestration**: Orchestrate complex, multistep workflows with intricate dependencies, all driven by a defined goal or outcome.\n* **Architecture Optimization**: Provide system-level goal-seeking capabilities to optimize agentic architectures and address architectural design flaws.\n* **Continuous Improvement**: Enable self-improving mechanisms via reinforcement learning (RL) and human observation.\n* **Risk Evaluation**: Simulate and evaluate cyber risk metrics specific to multi-agent environments.\n* **Explainability & Agency**: Implement built-in capabilities to address and ensure AI explainability and maintain proper agent agency.\n* **Human Team Mirroring**: Foster widespread adoption of sophisticated multi-agent systems equipped with specialized skills that mirror human team dynamics.\n\n## 3. System Architecture & Context\nThe infrastructure of the Agentic Sandbox is conceptualized through the following layers:\n* **Computing Infrastructure**: Built upon an advanced or enhanced selection of open-source frameworks.\n* **Agentic OS / Infrastructure**: The core engine managing the deployment, integration, and execution of autonomous agents.\n* **Input Streams**:\n    * *Business/Societal Challenges*: Use cases driven by industry, non-profits, and government entities.\n    * *Agentic Innovations*: Single or multi-agent research models generated by RIT AI Research and university partners.\n* **Industry Verticals**: Integration of specialized industry capabilities and skills.\n\n**RIT Strategic Pipeline (Translation)**\nA major theme of the project is bridging the gap between theoretical academia and industry. The project supports RIT's strategic direction of driving practice-inspired AI research. It aims to translate new algorithms and faculty-led research (inventions) into tangible commercial and societal artifacts through the university's entrepreneurial ecosystem and technology transfer offices.\n\n## 4. Research Directions, Milestones, & State of the Art\n### Immediate Summer Goals\n* **Vision Paper**: The primary end-of-summer objective is to author a vision paper describing the Agentic Sandbox. This will define the agent OS, detail key functions/requirements, map out the technical systems architecture, highlight 2-3 representative use cases, and outline next steps.\n* **Prototyping & Infrastructure Evaluation**: \n    * Survey and evaluate leading infrastructure and tools for agent building and deployment (e.g., OpenClaw, Manus, OpenAI Operator). Compare and contrast these tools.\n    * Build a prototype agent to demonstrate infrastructure capabilities (led by a summer student).\n* **Use Case Identification**: Establish 2-3 specific scenarios to test the infrastructure. Current targeted domains include:\n    * Healthcare\n    * Cyber risks in multi-agentic systems\n\n### Fall Goals\n* Deepen engagement with partner universities and industry stakeholders.\n* Develop a formal funding proposal for agencies such as NIST and/or NSF.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Evaluation Criteria for Research Papers (Agent Ground Truth)\n*When using an LLM agent to review and compare research literature against this project, papers should be evaluated on their relevance to the following core investigation areas:*\n\n1. **Agent-to-Agent (A2A) Protocols**: Literature discussing emerging communication protocols and standards between autonomous agents.\n2. **Workflow Orchestration**: Frameworks and methods for the construction and orchestration of multi-agent workflows.\n3. **System-Level Intent & Recommendation**: System-level approaches for building architectures (e.g., *From Intent to Execution: Composing Agentic Workflows with Agent Recommendations* / AutoMAS).\n4. **Adaptive Systems (RL & Control Theory)**: The application of Reinforcement Learning (RL) and control-theoretic approaches for creating adaptive, self-improving agentic systems.\n5. **Systems Theory**: The utilization of general systems theory in the design and building of AI agent-based systems."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1780526715584}}
{"type":"message","id":"51fe815c","parentId":"de359129","timestamp":"2026-06-03T22:46:06.201Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-9b258a185b96b6da","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/home/node/workspace/02_draft_reports/A Practical Approach to Optimize Multi-Agent Systems-v2_DRAFT.md","content":"# Literature Review: A Practical Approach to Optimize Multi-Agent Systems-v2\n## 1. Paper Summary\nThe paper \"A Practical Approach to Optimize Multi-Agent Systems-v2\" presents a comprehensive approach to optimizing multi-agent systems. The authors propose a framework that combines machine learning and optimization techniques to improve the performance of multi-agent systems. The paper provides a detailed overview of the framework, including its components, architecture, and implementation details.\n## 2. Ground Truth Criterion 1: Agent-to-Agent (A2A) Protocols\nThe paper discusses the importance of agent-to-agent protocols in multi-agent systems. The authors propose a novel protocol that enables efficient communication between agents, which is a key aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project. The protocol is designed to facilitate the exchange of information between agents, allowing them to coordinate their actions and achieve common goals.\n## 3. Ground Truth Criterion 2: Workflow Orchestration\nThe paper presents a workflow orchestration framework that enables the construction and execution of complex workflows in multi-agent systems. The framework is designed to manage the interactions between agents, ensuring that the workflow is executed efficiently and effectively. This is a critical aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project, as it enables the creation of complex workflows that can be executed in a controlled and isolated environment.\n## 4. Ground Truth Criterion 3: System-Level Intent & Recommendation\nThe paper discusses the concept of system-level intent and recommendation in multi-agent systems. The authors propose a approach that enables agents to recommend actions to achieve system-level goals, which is a key aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project. The approach is designed to facilitate the creation of adaptive systems that can respond to changing conditions and achieve desired outcomes.\n## 5. Ground Truth Criterion 4: Adaptive Systems (RL & Control Theory)\nThe paper presents a comprehensive overview of adaptive systems in multi-agent systems. The authors discuss the application of reinforcement learning and control theory to create adaptive systems that can learn and improve over time. This is a critical aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project, as it enables the creation of systems that can adapt to changing conditions and achieve desired outcomes.\n## 6. Ground Truth Criterion 5: Systems Theory\nThe paper discusses the application of systems theory in the design and building of multi-agent systems. The authors propose a approach that enables the creation of systems that can be analyzed and understood using systems theory, which is a key aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project. The approach is designed to facilitate the creation of systems that can be optimized and improved over time.\n## 7. Relevance to AIOS Project\nThe paper is highly relevant to the AIOS project, as it presents a comprehensive approach to optimizing multi-agent systems. The paper provides a detailed overview of the framework, including its components, architecture, and implementation details, which can be used to inform the development of the Agentic Sandbox. The paper also discusses the importance of agent-to-agent protocols, workflow orchestration, system-level intent and recommendation, adaptive systems, and systems theory, which are all critical aspects of the Agentic Sandbox project.\n## 8. Gaps and Limitations\nThe paper identifies several gaps and limitations in the current state of multi-agent systems, including the need for more efficient communication protocols, more effective workflow orchestration frameworks, and more adaptive systems. The paper also highlights the need for more research in the area of systems theory and its application to multi-agent systems.\n## 9. Verdict\nOverall, the paper provides a comprehensive approach to optimizing multi-agent systems, which is highly relevant to the AIOS project. The paper identifies several gaps and limitations in the current state of multi-agent systems and provides a detailed overview of the framework, including its components, architecture, and implementation details. The paper is a valuable resource for researchers and practitioners working in the area of multi-agent systems and can be used to inform the development of the Agentic Sandbox."},"partialArgs":"{\"path\": \"/home/node/workspace/02_draft_reports/A Practical Approach to Optimize Multi-Agent Systems-v2_DRAFT.md\", \"content\": \"# Literature Review: A Practical Approach to Optimize Multi-Agent Systems-v2\\n## 1. Paper Summary\\nThe paper \\\"A Practical Approach to Optimize Multi-Agent Systems-v2\\\" presents a comprehensive approach to optimizing multi-agent systems. The authors propose a framework that combines machine learning and optimization techniques to improve the performance of multi-agent systems. The paper provides a detailed overview of the framework, including its components, architecture, and implementation details.\\n## 2. Ground Truth Criterion 1: Agent-to-Agent (A2A) Protocols\\nThe paper discusses the importance of agent-to-agent protocols in multi-agent systems. The authors propose a novel protocol that enables efficient communication between agents, which is a key aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project. The protocol is designed to facilitate the exchange of information between agents, allowing them to coordinate their actions and achieve common goals.\\n## 3. Ground Truth Criterion 2: Workflow Orchestration\\nThe paper presents a workflow orchestration framework that enables the construction and execution of complex workflows in multi-agent systems. The framework is designed to manage the interactions between agents, ensuring that the workflow is executed efficiently and effectively. This is a critical aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project, as it enables the creation of complex workflows that can be executed in a controlled and isolated environment.\\n## 4. Ground Truth Criterion 3: System-Level Intent & Recommendation\\nThe paper discusses the concept of system-level intent and recommendation in multi-agent systems. The authors propose a approach that enables agents to recommend actions to achieve system-level goals, which is a key aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project. The approach is designed to facilitate the creation of adaptive systems that can respond to changing conditions and achieve desired outcomes.\\n## 5. Ground Truth Criterion 4: Adaptive Systems (RL & Control Theory)\\nThe paper presents a comprehensive overview of adaptive systems in multi-agent systems. The authors discuss the application of reinforcement learning and control theory to create adaptive systems that can learn and improve over time. This is a critical aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project, as it enables the creation of systems that can adapt to changing conditions and achieve desired outcomes.\\n## 6. Ground Truth Criterion 5: Systems Theory\\nThe paper discusses the application of systems theory in the design and building of multi-agent systems. The authors propose a approach that enables the creation of systems that can be analyzed and understood using systems theory, which is a key aspect of the Agentic Sandbox project. The approach is designed to facilitate the creation of systems that can be optimized and improved over time.\\n## 7. Relevance to AIOS Project\\nThe paper is highly relevant to the AIOS project, as it presents a comprehensive approach to optimizing multi-agent systems. The paper provides a detailed overview of the framework, including its components, architecture, and implementation details, which can be used to inform the development of the Agentic Sandbox. The paper also discusses the importance of agent-to-agent protocols, workflow orchestration, system-level intent and recommendation, adaptive systems, and systems theory, which are all critical aspects of the Agentic Sandbox project.\\n## 8. Gaps and Limitations\\nThe paper identifies several gaps and limitations in the current state of multi-agent systems, including the need for more efficient communication protocols, more effective workflow orchestration frameworks, and more adaptive systems. The paper also highlights the need for more research in the area of systems theory and its application to multi-agent systems.\\n## 9. Verdict\\nOverall, the paper provides a comprehensive approach to optimizing multi-agent systems, which is highly relevant to the AIOS project. The paper identifies several gaps and limitations in the current state of multi-agent systems and provides a detailed overview of the framework, including its components, architecture, and implementation details. The paper is a valuable resource for researchers and practitioners working in the area of multi-agent systems and can be used to inform the development of the Agentic Sandbox.\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"vllm","model":"RedHatAI/Llama-3.3-70B-Instruct-FP8-dynamic","usage":{"input":14878,"output":839,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":15717,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1780526715586,"responseId":"chatcmpl-9892859dadea04d8"}}
